properties.Title: Sasktel Service Outage Impacting Some Areas Of The Province
properties.Summary:
Description: Due to the widespread power outages caused by last night’s storm, SaskTel is experiencing some service outages in a number of communities across the province. Some communities have limited services at this time, and we anticipate more services may fail as back-up battery power depletes if commercial power is not restored. There is no estimated time of return for these services and it is likely that these services may not be restored until the power has been fully restored in these areas. Communities impacted include: Beechy, Herschel, Plenty, Dodsland, Saskatoon East, Lucky Lake, Warman, Meacham, Danielson (Diefenbaker Lake), Moose Jaw, Weyburn, Estevan.

Area: Saskatchewan

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A very strong frontal system will bring strong winds across the north coast, central coast, and northern Vancouver Island today and this evening. Winds will increase to southeast 80 to 100 km/h over Haida Gwaii this morning. These winds will spread to northern Vancouver Island and the central coast by this afternoon and then to the north coast late in the day. This evening, the system will move into the BC interior and away from the coastal regions. Following the passage of the front, the coastal areas will see the southeast winds shift to a southwest 50 to 70 km/h wind. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2021-01-15T04:45:44-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2021-01-14T12:46:44-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.3630008957.2021

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A frontal system approaching the northern Alaskan Panhandle will spread snow to the South Klondike Highway beginning this afternoon. Snow will intensify in the wake of the front on Friday as the flow switches to the southwest. Strong winds and heavy snow will combine to produce localized blowing snow on Friday. Total snowfall accumulations of 20 to 30 cm are expected near White Pass through Friday afternoon. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Potential for a heavy snowfall event this weekend. Snow is forecast to begin early Saturday morning as a strong low pressure system approaches Eastern Ontario from New England. This snow may then become heavy through the day Saturday and continue into Saturday night before easing Sunday. Significant snowfall amounts of 15 to 25 cm are possible by Sunday morning. Hazardous winter driving conditions are expected from this snowstorm. Motorists are advised to change travel plans accordingly. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard near the Richardson mountains overnight tonight and Friday. Very strong easterly winds will develop near the Richardson mountains overnight as an intense frontal system approaches. Peak winds of 90 gusting 110 km/h can be expected early Friday morning. These winds will combine with loose snow on the ground to produce blizzard conditions through Friday afternoon. Conditions are expected to improve late Friday as the winds ease in the wake of the front. ### Travel is expected to be very difficult or impossible due to near-zero visibility.
